03439nam a22005415i 9780300178371DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20112011ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001783717 a10.12987/97803001783712doi  a(DE-B1597)485758  a(OCoLC)759398132  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aHQ1061b.M534 2011eb 7aSOC0130002bisacsh04a305.260922221 aMiller, William Ian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLosing It :bIn which an Aging Professor laments his shrinking Brain. /cWilliam Ian Miller. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b4 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Losing It, William Ian Miller brings his inimitable wit and learning to the subject of growing old: too old to matter, of either rightly losing your confidence or wrongly maintaining it, culpably refusing to face the fact that you are losing it. The “it” in Miller’s “losing it” refers mainly to mental faculties-memory, processing speed, sensory acuity, the capacity to focus. But it includes other evidence as well-sags and flaccidities, aches and pains, failing joints and organs. What are we to make of these tell-tale signs? Does growing old gracefully mean more than simply refusing unseemly cosmetic surgeries? How do we face decline and the final drawing of the blinds? Will we know if and when we have lingered too long?Drawing on a lifetime of deep study and anxious observation, Miller enlists the wisdom of the ancients to confront these vexed questions head on. Debunking the glossy new image of old age that has accompanied the graying of the Baby Boomers, he conjures a lost world of aging rituals-complaints, taking to bed, resentments of one’s heirs, schemes for taking it with you or settling up accounts and scores-to remind us of the ongoing dilemmas of old age. Darkly intelligent and sublimely written, this exhilarating and eccentric book will raise the spirits of readers, young and old.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAging in literature. 0aAging. 0aOld age in literature. 0aOld age. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030017837140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300178371423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300178371/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles